The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, April 19, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, April 18: The government has began the exercise for drawing up an economic survey and Exim policy, even though they would be presented by the new government that assumes office after the elections in May. The preparation for the Union budget for 2004-05, is however, expected to start only after the new finance minister takes charge at north block, official sources said. There will be a proper economic survey and the preparation has already started, notwithstanding the fact that it will be presented by the new government, they said.																								 Mumbai, April 18: The Sebi will focus on improving the quality of intermediaries in 2004-05 and form a task force to recommend improvements in their infrastructure, including skills to prepare the market for handling large trading volumes in proposed T+1 settlement mode, said chairman G. N. Bajpai.																								 New Delhi, April 18: Life Insurance Corporation (LIC) has decided to give credit to infrastructure projects estimated at about Rs 12,000 crore in 2004-05, at a floating interest rate, said chairman S. B. Mathur.																								 Bokaro, April 18: Bokaro Steel Plant of SAIL is talking to Maruti Udyog Ltd for supply of low carbon steel specially being developed for the auto sector, said managing director U. P. Singh 																								 New Delhi, April 18: Navin Jindal promoted Jindal Power today said it has finalised a massive Rs 1,200 crore loan from IDBI, Bank of Baroda and State Bank of India to finance a 1000-MW power project, estimated to cost over Rs 2000 crore.
